HIV/AIDS: China reports an increase of 14% in new cases
China announced a 14% jump in the number of citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
More than 820,000 people are affected in the country, health authorities said.
About 40,000 new cases were reported only in the second quarter of 2018.
The vast majority of new cases result from transmissions through sexual relationships, which marks a change in relation to the past.
Traditionally, HIV has spread rapidly into some parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people who contracted HIV in this way has been reduced to almost zero, Chinese health authorities said at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, in terms of annual homologous variation, the number of living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000 people.
Transmission of HIV through sex is an acute problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalised in China in 1997, but discrimination against the LGBT community is said to be frequent.
Studies estimated that due to the conservative values of the country, 70 to 90% of men who had sex with other men eventually marry women.
Many of the disease transmissions derived from inadequate sexual protections in these relationships.
The Chinese government has since 2003 promised universal access to HIV medication as part of an effort to solve the problem.
