The latest design of this legendary technology character, Inrupt, is a company that takes advantage of the open source platform from Berners-Lee, Solid.
This allows users to decide where their data is stored and who has access to which information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joyfully stated that the intention underlying Inrupt is to “dominate the world.”
“We have to do so now,” he said about the startup.
"It's a historical moment."
The application uses Solid technology to allow people to create their own "personal online data warehouse", or POD.
This may contain contact lists, task lists, calendar, music library and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were all available in a single browser and simultaneously.
What is unique about the personal data store online is that it is exclusively to the user to decide who has access to which type of information.
The company calls it "personal capacity through data."
Inrupt’s idea, according to CEO of the company John Bruce, is to provide resources, processes, and the appropriate skills to help make Solid available to everyone.
The company is currently composed of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some internal programmers hired to work on the project and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology makers spread around the world will be able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to “Facebook and Google about the introduction or not of a total change in which all his business models are turned from one day to another.
"We are not asking for permission."
In a publication at Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that “Inrupt’s mission is to create commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new web created with Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he created the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on Internet neutrality.
Even while launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will continue to be the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I'm incredibly optimistic with this next era of the web," Berners-Lee added.
