The four vessels of the Baden-Württemberg class that the navy had ordered in 2007 will be used to replace the aged fregates of the Bremen class.
It is known that they will be equipped with a powerful cannon, as well as a series of anti-aircraft and anti-boat missiles, as well as some stealth technologies such as reducing radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include extended periods between maintenances, which would allow to send the latest fragatas in missions with a maximum duration of two years away from the ports of origin.
However, continuous delays have made that with the state-of-the-art warships, regarded as a form of Germany designing power beyond borders, will already be unprecedented when they come into service, refers the Die Zeit.
The unfortunate F125 fragate made headlines last year when the German navy refused to put it in service, having returned it to Blohm & Voss’s stations in Hamburg.
This was the first time the navy returned a ship to the ship after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but the German media quote a series of crucial "hardware and software defects" that would make the warship useless if used in a combat mission.
Software deficiencies were particularly important, since the ships of the Baden-Württemberg class will be operated by an crew of about 120 sailors, only half of the required contingent in the oldest fregats of the Bremen class.
It was also known that the vessel is excessively heavy, reducing its performance and limiting the ability of the navy to install additional features in the future.
It is believed that the 7000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz has twice the weight of similar class ships used by Germans in World War II.
In addition to hardware failures, the price of the whole project, including the formation of the crew, is also becoming a problem.
It is said that it will have reached a shocking 3.1 billion euros, an increase against 2.2 billion initially budgeted.
The problems that dissolve the latest fragatas have become particularly important in the light of the recent warnings that the German naval power is weakening.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, leader of the German parliamentary defence committee, acknowledged that the navy is currently leaving without ships capable of being used.
The politician claimed that the problem grew exponentially over time, as older ships were laid out of service without boats to replace them.
In the end, he regretted that none of the fragates of the Baden-Württemberg class could join the navy.
