Updated Information about the Red Mare: Concentrations decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to new information from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, a decrease in the Red Maré concentrations in some areas of the Tampa Bay has occurred.
The FWC reported that conditions of lower stain proliferation were identified in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
The stain of the Red Mare extends about 201 km along the coast, from Pinellas County north to Lee County south.
Stains can be found about 16 km along the coast of Hillsborough County, but in less areas than last week.
The Red Maré was also seen in the county of Pasco.
Last week, average concentrations were recorded along or along the coast of the county of Pinella, low concentrations along the coast of Hillsborough County, bottom concentrations along the coast of Manatee County, low bottom concentrations along or along the coast of the county of Sarasota County, bottom concentrations along the medium concentration of the county of Charlotte County.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Last week, there were no reports of respiratory irritation in the northwest region of Florida.
